This is a comprehensive design guide for the coding agent to build the "Creativity Boosters Interactive Dashboard" based on your provided implementation plan and reference image.

-----

## Design Guide: Creativity Boosters Command Center (V1 MVP)

**To the Coding Agent:**
This document translates the user's Implementation Plan and aesthetic preferences into specific technical design instructions. Your goal is to build a functional, visually premium, browser-based Kanban board using Vanilla JS, CSS, and HTML.

**Crucial Constraint:** NO frameworks (React, Vue, Bootstrap, Tailwind). All styling must be custom Vanilla CSS to maintain lightweight portability for GitHub Pages.

### 1\. Aesthetic Core & Design Philosophy

  * **Vibe:** Premium, energetic, modern, and professional creative. It should feel like stepping into the high-tech "studio" depicted in the reference image.
  * **Core Style:** **Dark Mode Glassmorphism**. The interface should feel like floating layers of frosted glass over a deep, technical background.
  * **Reference Imagery Integration:** The colors and energy of the attached podcast cover art must define the palette. The technical doodles in the background of the reference image should inspire subtle background patterns.

-----

### 2\. CSS Variables & Color Palette

Extracting from the reference image and the implementation plan, define these root variables in `style.css`.

```css
:root {
    /* --- Core Backgrounds --- */
    /* Deep Navy/Teal from image background corners */
    --bg-main: #0a192f; 
    /* Slightly lighter navy for gradients */
    --bg-secondary: #112240;
    
    /* --- Accents (From Image & Text) --- */
    /* Vibrant Orange/Gold from "BOOSTERS" text - Used for highlines & energy */
    --accent-primary: #FFAD00; 
    /* Neon Cyan from background tech doodles - Used for tech feel */
    --accent-secondary: #00E5FF;
    
    /* --- Semantic State Colors (Specified in Plan) --- */
    --state-idea: #8892b0;    /* Grey/Potential */
    --state-drafting: #FFC107; /* Yellow/Caution (Similar to primary accent) */
    --state-ready: #00C853;    /* Green/Go */
    --state-recorded: #2962FF; /* Blue/Done */

    /* --- Typography --- */
    --text-bright: #ffffff;
    --text-muted: #a8b2d1;
    --font-stack: 'Inter', 'Outfit', sans-serif; /* Import from Google Fonts */

    /* --- Glassmorphism Base Specs --- */
    /* Base color for glass cards */
    --glass-bg-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);
    /* Slightly more opaque for headers/active elements */
    --glass-bg-active: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
    --glass-border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
    --glass-blur: blur(12px);
    --shadow-soft: 0 8px 32px 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.37);
}
```

### 3\. Global Styles & Layout Structure (`index.html` & `style.css`)

**Background:** The `body` should have a dark gradient background. *Optional bonus:* Overlay a subtle, repeating SVG pattern of technical line-art (gears, sound waves, lightbulbs) similar to the reference image, set to very low opacity (5%).

**Typography:** Import fonts 'Outfit' (headings) and 'Inter' (body text) from Google Fonts.

**Layout Container:**
The main application needs a max-width container centered on the screen to maintain the "Command Center" feel.

```html
<body>
  <div id="app-container">
    <div id="login-overlay" class="glass-panel">...</div>

    <main id="dashboard">
        <header class="dashboard-header glass-panel">
            </header>
        <section class="kanban-board">
            </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</body>
```

-----

### 4\. UI Components & Behavioral Implementation Requirements

This section details how to code the specific behavioral design requests.

#### 4.1. The Glass Panel Class (Reusable Utility)

Create a utility class for anything that needs the "premium" look.

```css
.glass-panel {
    background: var(--glass-bg-color);
    backdrop-filter: var(--glass-blur);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: var(--glass-blur); /* Safari support */
    border-radius: 16px;
    border: var(--glass-border);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-soft);
    color: var(--text-bright);
}
```

#### 4.2. Header & Goal Gradient Progress Bar

**Requirement:** "A visual bar at the top showing Season Completion... Visual confetti/glow when hitting milestones."

  * **Header Design:** A thin glass panel spanning the top. It should contain the podcast title and the progress bar.
  * **Progress Bar Implementation:**
      * Container: A shallow, rounded track with a dark background (`rgba(0,0,0,0.3)`).
      * Fill Bar: A gradient moving from `var(--accent-secondary)` (Cyan) to `var(--accent-primary)` (Orange).
      * Milestones: Small circular markers placed at the 50% and 100% marks on the bar.
      * **Milestone Animation (CSS):** When the JS detects hitting 3/6 or 6/6, add a temporary class `glow-active` to the progress bar container.

<!-- end list -->

```css
/* Animation for Goal Gradient Milestone */
@keyframes milestoneGlow {
    0% { box-shadow: 0 0 5px var(--accent-primary); }
    50% { box-shadow: 0 0 25px var(--accent-primary), 0 0 50px var(--accent-secondary); }
    100% { box-shadow: 0 0 5px var(--accent-primary); }
}
.glow-active {
    animation: milestoneGlow 1.5s ease-in-out infinite;
}
```

#### 4.3. The Kanban Columns (Cognitive Fluency)

**Requirement:** "Semantic Colors mapped to columns."

  * **Structure:** The board is a flex container with 4 columns.
  * **Column Headers:** Each header needs a distinct border-top color corresponding to its semantic state variable (e.g., Ready column gets a green top border).

#### 4.4. The Task Cards (Frictionless Actions)

**Requirement:** "Drag-and-drop interface."

  * **Card Style:** Use the `.glass-panel` class. They should be sleek and compact.
  * **Draggable State:** Use Vanilla JS Drag and Drop API.
  * **Visual Feedback while Dragging:** When a card is lifted (`dragstart`), add a CSS class that increases its shadow, tilts it slightly, and increases brightness to make it feel physical.

<!-- end list -->

```css
.task-card[draggable="true"] {
    cursor: grab;
    transition: all 0.2s ease;
}
.task-card.is-dragging {
    opacity: 0.9;
    transform: rotate(3deg) scale(1.05);
    box-shadow: 0 15px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
    cursor: grabbing;
}
```

#### 4.5. The "Drafting" Column Special Effects (Zeigarnik Effect)

**Requirement:** "Subtle, pulsing border or 'unfinished' visual state... Red notification badge."

This is the most complex CSS requirement. The "Drafting" column needs unique treatment to create subconscious tension.

  * **The "Unfinished" Look:** The background of the *entire drafting column* should be slightly darker or more desaturated than the others, making it feel like a "hole" that needs filling.
  * **The Pulsing Border:** The cards *within* the drafting column need a subtle, restless animation.

<!-- end list -->

```css
/* Target cards ONLY inside the drafting column */
#column-drafting .task-card {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--state-drafting);
    animation: subtlePulse 4s infinite ease-in-out;
}

@keyframes subtlePulse {
    0% { border-color: rgba(255, 193, 7, 0.3); }
    50% { border-color: rgba(255, 193, 7, 1); box-shadow: inset 0 0 10px rgba(255, 193, 7, 0.2); }
    100% { border-color: rgba(255, 193, 7, 0.3); }
}
```

  * **Notification Badge:** A small, circular red span next to the "Drafting" header text. It should only be visible if the card count \> 0.

### 5\. Assets & Imagery Implementation

  * **Profile Pictures:** The provided reference image contains excellent caricatures of Dinko and Nikhil.
      * Extract these two faces into separate, circular PNGs with transparent backgrounds.
      * **Usage:** Use these small avatars on the task cards to assign responsibility (e.g., a small avatar in the corner of a card indicating "Dinko's Lead"). They can also be placed in the main Header next to the title.

### 6\. The Client-Side Login (Security through Obscurity)

  * **Visuals:** A centered `glass-panel` modal obscuring the rest of the app.
  * **Functionality (JS):** A simple input field and button. The JS checks the input against a hardcoded string (e.g., "creativityboom"). If it matches, set the login overlay to `display: none` and reveal the dashboard. *Reminder added to code comments: This is not real security, just a casual deterrent.*